---
// DISCOVERY — the history of Pluto's discovery.
// Seeded issues:
//   * discovery-plates image missing alt        (image-alt)
//   * link with an ARIA attr not allowed on it  (aria-allowed-attr)
//   * empty "share" link with no text           (link-name)
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout title="Discovery of Pluto" description="How Clyde Tombaugh discovered Pluto in 1930.">
  <h1>The Discovery of Pluto</h1>
  <p>
    In the late 1800s and early 1900s, astronomers noticed small irregularities
    in the orbit of Neptune and suspected an undiscovered "Planet X" was tugging
    on it. Percival Lowell, founder of the Lowell Observatory in Flagstaff,
    Arizona, began a dedicated search for this hypothetical world in 1906.
  </p>

  <section aria-labelledby="discTitle">
    <h2 id="discTitle">The search for Planet X</h2>
    <p>
      Lowell died in 1916 without finding Planet X. The search resumed in 1929
      when the observatory hired a 23-year-old Kansas farm boy and amateur
      astronomer named <strong>Clyde Tombaugh</strong>.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img src="/images/clyde-tombaugh.jpg" width="240" class="content-img"
           alt="Clyde Tombaugh, the astronomer who discovered Pluto in 1930." />
      <figcaption>Clyde W. Tombaugh, discoverer of Pluto.</figcaption>
    </figure>
  </section>

  <h2>Blinking the night sky</h2>
  <p>
    Tombaugh photographed the same patches of sky several nights apart and used a
    device called a <em>blink comparator</em> to rapidly switch between two plates.
    A planet would appear to jump back and forth against the fixed background
    stars. On 18 February 1930, while comparing plates taken in January, Tombaugh
    spotted a faint moving dot. Pluto had been found.
  </p>

  <!-- Image deliberately missing alt: image-alt -->
  <figure>
    <img src="/images/pluto-discovery-plates.png" width="520" class="content-img" />
    <figcaption>
      The discovery plates. Arrows mark Pluto's position on 23 and 29 January 1930.
    </figcaption>
  </figure>

  <p>
    The name "Pluto" — the Roman god of the underworld — was suggested by
    11-year-old Venetia Burney of England. The first two letters also honour
    Percival Lowell's initials.
    <!-- aria-pressed is not allowed on a link role (aria-allowed-attr) -->
    <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pluto" aria-pressed="false">Read
    more about how Pluto got its name</a>.
  </p>

  <!-- Empty link with no discernible text (link-name) -->
  <p>
    Share this page:
    <a href="#" class="icon-link" style="display:inline-block;width:1.5rem;height:1.5rem;background:#6b4fd6;border-radius:3px;"></a>
  </p>
</Layout>
